\title{Variational Derivation of the Euler--Lagrange Equation: Worked Notes}
\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
This document presents a worked derivation of the classical Euler--Lagrange equation in the calculus of variations. We treat functionals of the form
\[
J[y]=\int_a^b L\big(x,y(x),y'(x)\big)\,dx,
\]
where $y$ is assumed to be $C^2$ on $[a,b]$ and $L$ is sufficiently smooth. The goal is to compute the first variation $\delta J$ and deduce a necessary condition for $y$ to be stationary with respect to compactly supported variations $\eta$ with $\eta(a)=\eta(b)=0$.

In many applications the functional derives from a physical principle (for example, action integrals in mechanics) and the extremal equations carry direct interpretive meaning. We emphasize the formal steps so the same pattern can be applied to higher-order functionals or to problems with constraints.

\section{Derivation of the Euler--Lagrange equation}
We consider the one-parameter family $y_\varepsilon=y+\varepsilon\eta$. The variation of $J$ is
\begin{align}
\delta J&=\left.\frac{d}{d\varepsilon}J[y_\varepsilon]\right|_{\varepsilon=0}
=\left.\frac{d}{d\varepsilon}\int_a^b L\big(x,y_\varepsilon,y'_\varepsilon\big)\,dx\right|_{\varepsilon=0}\nonumber\\
&=\int_a^b\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial y}\eta+\frac{\partial L}{\partial y'}\eta'\right)\,dx.
\end{align}
Integrating the second term by parts and using $\eta(a)=\eta(b)=0$ gives
\[
\delta J=\int_a^b\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial y}-\frac{d}{dx}\frac{\partial L}{\partial y'}\right)\eta\,dx.
\]
By the fundamental lemma of the calculus of variations, the integrand must vanish for all admissible $\eta$, yielding the Euler--Lagrange equation:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:EL}
\frac{\partial L}{\partial y}-\frac{d}{dx}\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial y'}\right)=0.
\end{equation}
This is a second-order differential equation for $y(x)$ in the general first-order case. When $L$ has explicit $x$-dependence or additional fields are present, the same variational computation produces coupled systems.

Alternative viewpoint: the Gateaux derivative of $J$ in direction $\eta$ is
\[
D J[y](\eta)=\int_a^b\big(\partial_y L\,\eta+\partial_{y'}L\,\eta'\big)\,dx,
\]
and stationarity is equivalent to $D J[y](\eta)=0$ for all $\eta$ in the admissible class.

\section{Example: Geodesic on a cylinder}
As a concrete example, consider a cylinder of radius $R$ parametrized by coordinates $(\theta,z)$ and the length functional for a curve $\theta=\theta(z)$:
\[
J[\theta]=\int_{z_1}^{z_2} R\sqrt{\big(\theta'(z)\big)^2+1}\,dz.
\]
Here $L(\theta,\theta')=R\sqrt{1+(\theta')^2}$. Since $L$ does not depend explicitly on $\theta$, the corresponding momentum is conserved:
\[
\frac{\partial L}{\partial \theta'}=\frac{R\theta'}{\sqrt{1+(\theta')^2}}=C,
\]
which can be solved to give
\[
\theta'(z)=\frac{C}{\sqrt{R^2-C^2}}\quad\text{(constant)}.
\]
Thus the geodesics project to straight lines in the unwrapped rectangle, as expected. If the curve endpoints fix $\theta(z_1)$ and $\theta(z_2)$ then $C$ is determined by those boundary values. The same conservation law is a manifestation of Noether's theorem for the rotational symmetry in $\theta$.

\section{A theorem and its proof}
\begin{theorem}[Fundamental lemma]\label{thm:fundamental}
If $\int_a^b f(x)\eta(x)\,dx=0$ for all smooth $\eta$ vanishing at the endpoints, then $f(x)=0$ for all $x\in[a,b]$.
\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
Suppose $f$ is not identically zero. Then there exists an interval where $f$ maintains a sign; choosing $\eta$ supported in that interval and of the appropriate sign yields a contradiction. A standard construction uses bump functions to localize the test function $\eta$. This argument accommodates piecewise-continuous $f$ under the usual integrability assumptions.
\end{proof}

\section{Remarks and extensions}
Natural boundary conditions appear when the class of admissible variations does not fix endpoint values; the integrated-by-parts term produces boundary contributions. For higher-order functionals one finds Euler--Lagrange equations of correspondingly higher order and additional boundary conditions.

\section{Conclusion}
The preceding notes summarize a standard derivation and provide a geometric example. Equation (\ref{eq:EL}) is a local necessary condition for extremals of first-order functionals. In applied problems one must combine (\ref{eq:EL}) with boundary or transversality conditions. Variational principles remain a unifying language across mechanics, geometry, and control theory.

