\section*{Outline: Spectral theorem for compact self-adjoint operators}
This note presents a concise outline of the proof that a compact self-adjoint operator on a separable Hilbert space has an orthonormal basis of eigenvectors. The exposition is informal but contains the main steps and key estimates used in standard texts. Multiple display equations and short derivations are included to make the logical flow explicit.

\subsection*{Preliminaries}
Let \mathcal{H} be an infinite-dimensional separable Hilbert space and let T:\mathcal{H}\to\mathcal{H} be compact and self-adjoint. We denote the inner product by \langle x,y\rangle and the norm by \|x\|. The spectrum \sigma(T) is real and any nonzero \lambda\in\sigma(T) is an eigenvalue. Compactness implies the only possible accumulation point of \sigma(T) is 0: if \lambda\neq 0 then \lambda is isolated and of finite multiplicity.

\subsection*{Main statement}
\begin{theorem}
Let T be as above. Then there exists an orthonormal sequence \{e_n\}_{n=1}^\infty of eigenvectors of T such that
\[
Tx=\sum_{n=1}^\infty \lambda_n \langle x,e_n\rangle e_n,
\]
for every x\in\mathcal{H}, where \lambda_n\to 0 and the series converges in norm.
\end{theorem}

\subsection*{Key lemmas}
\begin{lemma}
There exists x of unit norm with \|Tx\|=\|T\|. Any such x is an eigenvector corresponding to an eigenvalue of modulus \|T\|.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Define the numerical radius r=\sup_{\|x\|=1} |\langle Tx,x\rangle| and note r\le\|T\|. Using compactness, choose a sequence x_k with \|x_k\|=1 and \|Tx_k\|\to\|T\|. Extract a convergent subsequence of Tx_k, say Tx_{k_j}\to y. Then one verifies that T attains its norm and that y is a scalar multiple of the corresponding x, hence an eigenvector. More explicitly, consider
\[
\|Tx_k\|^2 = \langle T^2 x_k, x_k\rangle \to \|T\|^2,
\]
and pass to the limit to conclude
\[
T^2 x = \|T\|^2 x,
\]
which implies T x = \pm\|T\| x because T is self-adjoint.
\end{proof}

\subsection*{Proof outline}
We construct iteratively an orthonormal set of eigenvectors. Suppose e_1,...,e_{n-1} have been chosen with eigenvalues \lambda_1,...,\lambda_{n-1}. Consider the restriction T_n of T to the orthogonal complement of \operatorname{span}\{e_1,...,e_{n-1}\}. By the lemma, T_n attains its norm at some unit vector e_n which is an eigenvector for T_n and hence for T. The corresponding eigenvalue \lambda_n satisfies |\lambda_n|\le|\lambda_{n-1}|. If the sequence does not terminate at zero, compactness ensures \lambda_n\to 0.

To verify completeness, suppose the closed linear span of the e_n is not all of \mathcal{H}. Then there exists a nonzero vector x orthogonal to every e_n. Consider the Rayleigh quotient restricted to the closure of the span of x and the e_n. Because x is orthogonal to all constructed eigenvectors, the restriction of T to this invariant subspace has norm strictly less than the maximum encountered in the construction, contradicting how e_n were chosen to realize successive maxima. A more direct contradiction arises by constructing approximate eigenvectors with spectral value bounded away from zero, in conflict with the fact that eigenvalues must tend to 0. Thus the span is dense and the expansion in the theorem holds.

\subsection*{Remarks and variants}
The finite-dimensional case reduces to the classical diagonalization of symmetric matrices. The argument extends to compact normal operators on complex Hilbert spaces: one replaces real eigenvalues by complex ones and obtains a complete orthonormal system of eigenvectors. For unbounded operators the situation is more delicate and requires functional calculus and domain considerations; the compactness assumption is essential in this outline.

