Introduction

These notes present a worked derivation of the classical solution formula for the one-dimensional heat equation on the real line and a short uniqueness proof. We emphasize the use of the Fourier transform and convolution estimates so that the steps are explicit and suitable for teaching. All LaTeX commands, labels, and displayed equations are preserved for clarity.

Problem and formal transform

Consider the initial value problem
\begin{equation}\label{eq:heat}
\partial_t u(x,t) = \kappa \partial_{xx} u(x,t), \qquad u(x,0)=u_0(x),
\end{equation}
for $x\in\mathbb{R}$, $t>0$, and thermal diffusivity $\kappa>0$. We take the Fourier transform in $x$ defined by $\mathcal{F}\{f\}(\xi)=\int_{\mathbb{R}} e^{-i x\xi} f(x)\,dx$; denote this operator by $\mathcal{F}$ throughout. Applying $\mathcal{F}$ to \eqref{eq:heat} yields the ODE
\begin{equation}\label{eq:fourier}
\partial_t \hat u(\xi,t) = -\kappa \xi^2 \hat u(\xi,t), \qquad \hat u(\xi,0)=\hat u_0(\xi).
\end{equation}
This linear ODE has the explicit solution
\begin{equation}\label{eq:fourier_solution}
\hat u(\xi,t) = e^{-\kappa \xi^2 t} \hat u_0(\xi).
\end{equation}
Inverting the Fourier transform gives the convolution representation below.

Solution formula and kernel properties

Taking the inverse transform of \eqref{eq:fourier_solution} yields the classical Gaussian kernel representation
\begin{equation}\label{eq:solution}
u(x,t) = (G_t * u_0)(x), \qquad G_t(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{4\pi\kappa t}} e^{-x^2/(4\kappa t)}.
\end{equation}
Here $*$ denotes convolution in $x$. The kernel $G_t$ satisfies the normalization $\int_{\mathbb{R}} G_t(x)\,dx=1$ for $t>0$ and approximates the identity as $t\downarrow 0$.

Lemma and convolution estimate

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:conv}
If $u_0\in L^1(\mathbb{R})$ then $\lim_{t\downarrow 0} \|G_t * u_0 - u_0\|_{L^1}=0$.
\end{lemma}

By Lemma \ref{lem:conv} and the explicit formula \eqref{eq:solution} we see that $\lim_{t\downarrow 0} u(\cdot,t)=u_0$ in $L^1$. The standard proof uses approximation by continuous compactly supported functions and the fact that $G_t$ is an approximate identity. In particular, for any $\epsilon > 0$ one chooses a continuous $\phi$ with compact support such that $\|u_0-\phi\|_{L^1}<\epsilon/3$, and then uses uniform continuity of $\phi$ to bound the convolution error.

Uniqueness theorem and proof

\begin{theorem}\label{thm:unique}
Let $u,v\in C([0,T];L^1(\mathbb{R}))$ be two mild solutions of \eqref{eq:heat} with the same initial datum $u_0\in L^1(\mathbb{R})$. Then $u(x,t)=v(x,t)$ for all $x\in\mathbb{R}$ and $t\in[0,T]$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
Consider the difference $w=u-v$. Then $w$ satisfies the homogeneous equation with zero initial data. Using the convolution representation for each solution we have
\begin{align}
\|w(\cdot,t)\|_{L^1} &= \|G_t * u_0 - G_t * v_0\|_{L^1} = \|G_t * (u_0-v_0)\|_{L^1} \nonumber \\
&\le \|G_t\|_{L^1} \|u_0-v_0\|_{L^1} = 0.
\end{align}
Since $u_0=v_0$, the right-hand side vanishes and hence $\|w(\cdot,t)\|_{L^1}=0$ for each $t$, which implies $w\equiv0$ and the solutions coincide.
\end{proof}

Worked example

Take $u_0(x)=e^{-x^2}$. Then the Fourier transform is $\hat u_0(\xi)=\sqrt{\pi} e^{-\xi^2/4}$, so by \eqref{eq:fourier_solution}
\[\hat u(\xi,t)=\sqrt{\pi} e^{-\xi^2(\frac14+\kappa t)}.\]
Inverting yields another Gaussian and one computes explicitly that $u(x,t) = \sqrt{\frac{1}{1+4\kappa t}} \exp\left(-\frac{x^2}{1+4\kappa t}\right)$, consistent with \eqref{eq:solution} after normalization.

Figure (for illustration)

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
% (Plot of G_t omitted)
\caption{Solution kernel for the heat equation at several times $t>0$.}
\end{figure}

Conclusion

The Fourier method gives a direct route to both existence and classical properties of solutions for the heat equation on the whole line. The convolution kernel is explicit, smooth for $t>0$, and yields immediate continuity and uniqueness results as shown above.

