\section*{Abstract}
This extract reports on a laboratory measurement of diffusion coefficients in a aqueous gel matrix. The aim is to demonstrate derivations and error analysis typical for a lab report that includes LaTeX math, a short theorem statement, and numbered derivations. The concentration field is denoted by $c(x,t)$ and the diffusivity by $D$; measurements were made at three temperatures.

\section{Introduction}
Diffusion in porous media is often modeled by the diffusion equation. For a one-dimensional, homogeneous medium we write
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial c}{\partial t} = D \frac{\partial^2 c}{\partial x^2},
\label{eq:diffusion}
\end{equation}
where $c$ has units mol m$^{-3}$ and $D$ has units m$^2$ s$^{-1}$. Temperature dependence of $D$ is often approximated by an Arrhenius relation,
$D = D_0 \exp\left(-\frac{E_a}{k_B T}\right)$,
with activation energy $E_a$ and Boltzmann constant $k_B$.

\begin{theorem}[Fick's First Law]
For steady-state diffusion in a slab, the flux $J$ is proportional to the concentration gradient:
\begin{equation}
J = -D \frac{\partial c}{\partial x}.
\end{equation}
\end{theorem}

\section{Methods}
Samples of gel (thickness $L=5\ \text{mm}$) were prepared and a tracer was applied at $x=0$. Concentration profiles $c(x,t)$ were measured by optical absorbance at discrete times. The experimental $\Delta V$ for injected volume was $0.50\ \text{mL}$ with an uncertainty of $\pm 0.02\ \text{mL}$. Calibration gives concentration from absorbance via $c = \alpha A$, where $\alpha$ is determined from standards.

We performed a linear regression on the logarithm of $D$ versus $1/T$ to extract $E_a$. The derivation below shows the algebra for converting measured profiles to a diffusion coefficient.

\section{Derivation}
Starting from (\ref{eq:diffusion}) and assuming an initial step concentration, separation of variables yields solutions of the form $c(x,t) = \sum_{n} a_n \exp(-\lambda_n^2 D t)\phi_n(x)$. For the dominant mode, an effective time constant $\tau$ satisfies $\tau^{-1} = \lambda_1^2 D$.

A short derivation:
\begin{align}
\langle x^2 \rangle(t) &= \int x^2 c(x,t)\,dx \approx 2 D t + \mathrm{const}, \\
D &= \frac{1}{2}\frac{d}{dt}\langle x^2 \rangle(t).
\end{align}

\section{Results and Discussion}
Measured values at $T=293,\ 303,\ 313\ \text{K}$ gave $D=(2.1\pm0.2)\times10^{-10},\ (3.3\pm0.3)\times10^{-10},\ (5.0\pm0.5)\times10^{-10}\ \text{m}^2\text{s}^{-1}$ respectively. Error propagation combined instrument noise and calibration uncertainty. The Arrhenius fit produced $E_a=(18\pm2)\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}$.

Figure \ref{fig:profiles} shows representative concentration profiles and the fit lines used to obtain $D$.

