\section{Introduction}
These notes present a concise worked exposition of the spectral theorem for normal matrices and a sample derivation that illustrates common manipulations with inner products and unitary diagonalization. The intended reader is assumed to be familiar with basic linear algebra: eigenvalues, eigenvectors, and inner-product notation such as $x^*y$ for the conjugate transpose pairing. The emphasis is on step-by-step algebraic manipulations suitable for classroom use.

\section{Preliminaries}
Let $A\in\mathbb{C}^{n\times n}$ be a normal matrix, i.e. $A^*A = AA^*$. Recall that a matrix is unitary if $U^*U = I$. Throughout, vectors are column vectors and $\|x\|^2 = x^*x$ denotes the squared norm. We will use the standard fact that normal matrices are unitarily diagonalizable.

\begin{theorem}\label{thm:spectral}
Let $A\in\mathbb{C}^{n\times n}$ be normal. Then there exists a unitary matrix $U$ and a diagonal matrix $\Lambda = \mathrm{diag}(\lambda_1,\dots,\lambda_n)$ such that
\begin{equation}\label{eq:spectral}
A = U\Lambda U^*.
\end{equation}
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
We sketch a standard constructive proof. Choose an orthonormal basis of eigenvectors $\{u_1,\dots,u_n\}$ for $A$ (possible because $A$ is normal). Form $U=[u_1\;\dots\;u_n]$ and let $\Lambda$ be the diagonal matrix of corresponding eigenvalues. Then for each basis vector $u_j$ we have $Au_j = \lambda_j u_j$, and therefore $AU = U\Lambda$. Multiplying on the right by $U^*$ gives $A = U\Lambda U^*$, and unitarity of $U$ follows from the orthonormality of the eigenvectors.
\end{proof}

\section{A Sample Derivation}
We now derive a short identity that is useful when comparing norms of $Ax$ and $A^*x$ for arbitrary $x$. Start from the definition and use the spectral factorization \eqref{eq:spectral}.
\begin{align}
\|Ax\|^2 &= x^* A^* A x \\
&= x^* (U\Lambda^* U^*)(U\Lambda U^*) x \\
&= x^* U \Lambda^* \Lambda U^* x \\
&= (U^* x)^* (\Lambda^*\Lambda) (U^* x). \label{eq:energy}
\end{align}
The intermediate step uses $A^* = U\Lambda^* U^*$, which follows by taking conjugate transposes of \eqref{eq:spectral}. Equation \eqref{eq:energy} shows that the squared norm of $Ax$ depends only on the magnitudes $|\lambda_j|^2$ and the components of $U^*x$.

As a concrete illustration, consider a $2\times2$ unitary rotation matrix
\begin{equation}
R(\theta) = \begin{pmatrix}\cos\theta & -\sin\theta \\
\sin\theta & \cos\theta\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}
Its eigenvalues are $e^{\pm i\theta}$, and one may verify Euler's formula $e^{i\theta} = \cos\theta + i\sin\theta$ when computing the diagonal form.

\section{Remarks on Numerical Considerations}
When implementing the diagonalization in floating point arithmetic, one must account for rounding errors in orthogonality of computed eigenvectors. It is customary to reorthogonalize or to use stable routines such as the QR algorithm. The derivation above is algebraic and exact; in practice, verify residuals by checking $\|A - U\Lambda U^*\|$ and by confirming that $U^*U \approx I$ to within machine precision.

\section{Conclusion}
This worked note has recalled the spectral theorem, given a short proof sketch, and demonstrated a derivation that reduces norm computations to diagonal entries. The labels \eqref{eq:spectral} and \eqref{eq:energy} are provided for cross-reference in later material and in exercises that ask the student to reproduce and extend these steps.

%% Derivation sheet: Lagrangian approach to wave equation
\section*{Introduction}
This note presents a streamlined derivation of the classical one-dimensional wave equation using a continuum Lagrangian formalism.  The goal is to make explicit the variational steps and to display energy conservation in the same framework.  The field of interest is a scalar displacement field $u(x,t)$ representing, for example, transverse displacement of a stretched string.  We use a Lagrangian density $\mathcal{L}(u,\partial_t u,\partial_x u)$ and the standard Euler--Lagrange procedure.

\section*{Lagrangian density and Euler--Lagrange}
Consider the Lagrangian density
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L} = \frac{1}{2}\rho (\partial_t u)^2 - \frac{1}{2}T(\partial_x u)^2 - V(u),
\label{eq:lagrangian}
\end{equation}
where $\rho$ is the linear mass density, $T$ is the tension, and $V(u)$ is a potential that can include external forces or nonlinear restoring terms.  The action is
\begin{equation}
S[u] = \int_{t_1}^{t_2}\!dt\int_{x_1}^{x_2}\!dx\,\mathcal{L}.
\end{equation}
Applying the Euler--Lagrange equation for fields,
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_t u)}\right) + \frac{\partial}{\partial x}\left(\frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial(\partial_x u)}\right) - \frac{\partial\mathcal{L}}{\partial u} = 0,
\label{eq:EL}
\end{equation}
one obtains the equation of motion.  Substituting \eqref{eq:lagrangian} gives
\begin{align}
\rho\,\partial_{tt} u - T\,\partial_{xx} u + V'(u) &= 0.
\label{eq:general_motion}
\end{align}
For small displacements about a reference configuration with negligible external potential, set $V(u)=0$ and arrive at the linear wave equation.

\section*{Derivation of the linear wave equation}
With $V(u)=0$, equation \eqref{eq:general_motion} simplifies to
\begin{equation}
\rho\,\partial_{tt} u - T\,\partial_{xx} u = 0.
\label{eq:wave}
\end{equation}
Dividing by $\rho$ and defining the wave speed $c=\sqrt{T/\rho}$ yields the canonical form
\begin{equation}
\partial_{tt} u - c^2\partial_{xx} u = 0.
\end{equation}
This is the one-dimensional wave equation, valid in the interior $x_1<x<x_2$ for times $t_1<t<t_2$, subject to appropriate boundary and initial conditions.

\begin{theorem}[Energy conservation]
For solutions of \eqref{eq:wave} with smooth decay or fixed boundary conditions, the energy
\begin{equation}
E(t) = \int_{x_1}^{x_2}\left( \frac{1}{2}\rho (\partial_t u)^2 + \frac{1}{2}T(\partial_x u)^2 \right)dx
\label{eq:energy}
\end{equation}
is conserved in time: $dE/dt=0$.
\end{theorem}

\proof
Differentiate \eqref{eq:energy} with respect to $t$ and use the equation of motion \eqref{eq:wave}:
\begin{align}
\frac{dE}{dt} &= \int_{x_1}^{x_2} \left(\rho\,\partial_t u\,\partial_{tt} u + T\,\partial_x u\,\partial_{xt} u\right)dx \nonumber \\
&= \int_{x_1}^{x_2} \partial_t u\, (\rho\,\partial_{tt} u - T\,\partial_{xx} u)\,dx + T\,\partial_x u\,\partial_t u\Big|_{x_1}^{x_2}.
\end{align}
The bulk integral vanishes by \eqref{eq:wave} and the boundary term vanishes for fixed or periodic boundary conditions, yielding $dE/dt=0$.
\qed

\section*{Example: string with fixed ends}
As an illustrative example set $x\in[0,L]$ with $u(0,t)=u(L,t)=0$.  The normal-mode expansion uses separation of variables $u(x,t)=X(x)T(t)$, leading to eigenfunctions $X_n(x)=\sin(n\pi x/L)$ and eigenfrequencies $\omega_n = n\pi c/L$.  A general solution is
\begin{equation}
 u(x,t)=\sum_{n=1}^\infty\left[A_n\cos(\omega_n t)+B_n\sin(\omega_n t)\right]\sin\left(\frac{n\pi x}{L}\right),
\end{equation}
with coefficients determined by initial displacement and velocity profiles.

\section*{Remarks}
The Lagrangian approach readily generalizes to higher dimensions, elastic media, and coupled fields.  Nonlinear potentials $V(u)$ produce richer dynamics including solitons in special cases.  The compact variational derivation presented here serves as a template for more advanced continuum mechanical models.

