\section*{Abstract}
This laboratory extract reports an analytical treatment and selected experimental context for a first-order electrophysiological model with buffer-controlled ionic currents. The document combines a concise derivation of the model response with a brief Methods and Results discussion suitable for replication. Multiple inline formulae and display equations are preserved exactly to allow direct comparison between theory and lab observations.

\section{Introduction}
We consider a single-compartment membrane potential $V(t)$ subject to a leaky integrator dynamics with an imposed input current $I(t)$. The theoretical basis is the linear ordinary differential equation
\begin{equation}\label{eq:diff_eq}
\tau \frac{dV}{dt} + V = V_\infty + I(t),
\end{equation}
where $\tau$ is the membrane time constant and $V_\infty$ denotes the resting potential in the absence of input. For a constant input $I(t)=k$, the steady-state solution satisfies $V_{\mathrm{ss}} = V_\infty + k$ and transient behavior follows exponential relaxation.

\begin{theorem}[Uniqueness]\label{thm:uniq}
Given initial condition $V(0)=V_0$ and continuous input $I(t)$ on $[0,T]$, the solution of (\ref{eq:diff_eq}) is unique and continuously differentiable on $[0,T]$.
\end{theorem}

A constructive proof follows from integrating factor methods and is summarized in the Methods section.

\section{Methods}
Experiments were conducted at room temperature with physiological buffer (pH 7.4) and cells held at $37^\circ\mathrm{C}$ during stimulation. The input protocol was a step current of amplitude $k=3.5\,\mu\mathrm{A}$ for $t\in[0,\,\infty)$ in one series, and a pulsed input in another. Analytical solutions were obtained using an integrating factor; numerical verification used a fourth-order Runge--Kutta solver with time step $\Delta t=0.1\,\mathrm{ms}$.

Derivation (integrating factor): multiply (\ref{eq:diff_eq}) by $e^{t/\tau}$ to obtain
\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(e^{t/\tau}V(t)\right)=\frac{e^{t/\tau}}{\tau} \big(V_\infty + I(t)\big).
\end{equation}
Integrating from $0$ to $t$ gives the general solution
\begin{align}\label{eq:solution}
V(t) &= V_0 e^{-t/\tau} + \int_0^t \frac{e^{-(t-s)/\tau}}{\tau} \big(V_\infty + I(s)\big)\, ds \\
&= V_0 e^{-t/\tau} + V_\infty\left(1-e^{-t/\tau}\right) + \int_0^t \frac{e^{-(t-s)/\tau}}{\tau} I(s)\, ds. \nonumber
\end{align}
For constant $I(s)=k$ this reduces to the closed form used in Results.

\section{Results}
Substituting $I(t)=k$ into (\ref{eq:solution}) yields
\begin{equation}
V(t)=V_0 e^{-t/\tau} + V_\infty\left(1-e^{-t/\tau}\right) + k\left(1-e^{-t/\tau}\right).
\end{equation}
Rearranging provides the compact expression
\begin{equation}
V(t) = V_{\mathrm{ss}} - (V_{\mathrm{ss}}-V_0)e^{-t/\tau}, \qquad V_{\mathrm{ss}}=V_\infty + k.
\end{equation}
Representative traces recorded experimentally are shown in Figure~1 and track the theoretical curve with a best-fit $\tau=12.4\,\mathrm{ms}$. Residuals remain below 5\% for the steady-state amplitude.

\section{Discussion}
The model captures the primary dynamics observed in our buffer-controlled experiments. Deviations arise when nonlinear conductances activate at larger depolarizations or when the buffer composition departs from pH 7.4. The uniqueness theorem guarantees that observed variability stems from parameter differences rather than ill-posedness of the forward problem.

\section{Conclusion}
This extract provides a self-contained derivation of the leaky integrator model and contextualizes it with experimental conditions. The analytic solution (\ref{eq:solution}) offers a convenient baseline for parameter estimation and hypothesis testing.

