Introduction

This derivation sheet presents a self-contained treatment of the one-dimensional wave equation for a homogeneous elastic string. The primary unknown is the transverse displacement $u(x,t)$ with $x\in[0,L]$ and time $t\ge0$. We start from a discrete mass-spring chain and pass to the continuum limit, then derive conservation statements and an energy theorem.

1. From discrete chain to continuum

Consider a chain of masses $m$ separated by distance $\Delta x$ and connected by springs with stiffness $k$. Let $u_i(t)$ denote the transverse displacement of the $i$-th mass. The linearized equation of motion for internal masses is

\begin{equation}\label{eq:discrete}
 m\ddot u_i = k(u_{i+1}-u_i) - k(u_i-u_{i-1}).
\end{equation}

Divide by $\Delta x$ and write density $\rho=m/\Delta x$ and tension parameter $T=k\Delta x$. Taking the limit $\Delta x\to0$ with $\rho$ and $T$ fixed yields the wave equation

\begin{equation}\label{eq:wave}
 \rho\,\partial_{tt} u = T\,\partial_{xx} u.
\end{equation}

It is customary to set $c^2 = T/\rho$, so that

\begin{equation}\label{eq:wave2}
 \partial_{tt} u - c^2\partial_{xx} u = 0.
\end{equation}

Boundary and initial conditions may be prescribed, for example Dirichlet boundaries $u(0,t)=u(L,t)=0$ and initial data

\begin{equation}
 u(x,0)=u_0(x),\qquad \partial_t u(x,0)=v_0(x).
\end{equation}

2. Energy identity

Define the energy density

\begin{equation}
 e(x,t) = \tfrac12\rho(\partial_t u)^2 + \tfrac12 T(\partial_x u)^2.
\end{equation}

Integrating over the domain and differentiating under the integral sign gives the total energy

\begin{equation}\label{eq:energy}
 E(t)=\int_0^L e(x,t)\,dx.
\end{equation}

A short computation using \eqref{eq:wave2} yields

\begin{align}
 \frac{dE}{dt} &= \int_0^L \big(\rho\partial_t u\,\partial_{tt} u + T\partial_x u\,\partial_{xt} u\big)\,dx \\
 &= \int_0^L \partial_t u\,(\rho\partial_{tt} u - T\partial_{xx} u)\,dx + T\partial_x u\,\partial_t u\Big|_0^L \\
 &= T\partial_x u\,\partial_t u\Big|_0^L.
\end{align}

Thus, for homogeneous Dirichlet or Neumann boundary conditions that enforce $\partial_t u=0$ or $\partial_x u=0$ on the boundary, the boundary term vanishes and energy is conserved:

\begin{theorem}
 (Energy conservation) Suppose $u$ satisfies \eqref{eq:wave2} with boundary conditions that make the boundary term zero. Then $E(t)=E(0)$ for all $t\ge0$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
 The computation above shows $dE/dt=0$ under the stated boundary conditions, hence $E(t)$ is constant in time. More precisely, integrate the identity resulting from multiplying \eqref{eq:wave2} by $\partial_t u$ over $[0,L]$ and use integration by parts to obtain \eqref{eq:energy}--the boundary term vanishes.
\end{proof}

3. Modal expansion and example

With Dirichlet boundary conditions one may use the orthonormal sine basis $\sin(n\pi x/L)$. Seek separable solutions $u(x,t)=X(x)T(t)$, leading to

\begin{equation}
 X''+\lambda X=0,\qquad T''+c^2\lambda T=0.
\end{equation}

Imposing $X(0)=X(L)=0$ yields eigenvalues $\lambda_n=(n\pi/L)^2$ and eigenmodes

\begin{equation}
 u_n(x,t)=A_n\cos(c n\pi t/L)\sin(n\pi x/L)+B_n\sin(c n\pi t/L)\sin(n\pi x/L).
\end{equation}

The coefficients $A_n,B_n$ are obtained from the initial data by Fourier sine expansion. Energy decomposes into a sum over modal energies, which is useful for numerical truncation.

4. Remarks and extensions

The same derivation extends to an inhomogeneous string with spatially varying density $\rho(x)$ and tension $T(x)$, leading to the generalized form

\[ \rho(x)\partial_{tt} u - \partial_x\big(T(x)\partial_x u\big) = 0. \]

Damping or external forcing terms can be added on the right-hand side. The energy identity then acquires source or dissipation terms and can be used to derive stability estimates.

