\section*{Outline of proof for the Poisson problem}
This note outlines a standard variational proof of existence and uniqueness for the boundary value problem
\begin{equation}\label{eq:strong}
-\Delta u = f \quad\text{in }\Omega, \qquad u=0 \quad\text{on }\partial\Omega,
\end{equation}
where \(\Omega\subset\mathbb{R}^n\) is a bounded Lipschitz domain and \(f\in H^{-1}(\Omega)\). The presentation is intended as a concise proof outline rather than a complete exposition; key lemmas are stated and then invoked in the main argument.

\section*{Weak formulation and main theorem}
Introduce the energy space \(H^1_0(\Omega)\). The weak form of (\ref{eq:strong}) reads: find \(u\in H^1_0(\Omega)\) such that
\begin{equation}\label{eq:weakform}
a(u,v) = L(v) \quad\text{for all } v\in H^1_0(\Omega),
\end{equation}
where the bilinear form and linear functional are
\begin{gather*}
a(u,v) := \int_\Omega \nabla u\cdot\nabla v\,dx, \\
L(v) := \langle f, v\rangle_{H^{-1}\times H^1_0}.
\end{gather*}
The main statement is the following.

\begin{theorem}\label{thm:existence}
Assume \(\Omega\) is bounded and Lipschitz and \(f\in H^{-1}(\Omega)\). Then there exists a unique solution \(u\in H^1_0(\Omega)\) of (\ref{eq:weakform}). Moreover, the solution satisfies the a priori estimate
\begin{equation}\label{eq:apriori}
\|u\|_{H^1_0(\Omega)} \le C\,\|f\|_{H^{-1}(\Omega)}
\end{equation}
for some constant \(C>0\) depending only on \(\Omega\).
\end{theorem}

\section*{Proof outline}
The proof is a direct application of the Lax--Milgram theorem. We verify the two hypotheses: continuity and coercivity of the bilinear form \(a\), and continuity of the linear functional \(L\).

Continuity: By the Cauchy--Schwarz inequality and the definition of the \(H^1_0\)-norm,
\begin{equation}\label{eq:cont}
|a(u,v)| = \left|\int_\Omega \nabla u\cdot\nabla v\,dx\right| \le \|\nabla u\|_{L^2(\Omega)}\,\|\nabla v\|_{L^2(\Omega)} = \|u\|_{H^1_0(\Omega)}\,\|v\|_{H^1_0(\Omega)}.
\end{equation}
Thus \(a\) is continuous with constant \(M=1\).

Coercivity: The bilinear form satisfies
\begin{equation}\label{eq:coercive}
a(v,v) = \|\nabla v\|_{L^2(\Omega)}^2 \ge C_P^{-2}\,\|v\|_{H^1_0(\Omega)}^2,
\end{equation}
where we invoked the Poincar\'e inequality with constant \(C_P\). Hence \(a\) is coercive with coercivity constant \(\alpha=C_P^{-2}>0\).

Continuity of \(L\): By definition of the dual norm,
\begin{equation}
|L(v)| = |\langle f,v\rangle| \le \|f\|_{H^{-1}(\Omega)}\,\|v\|_{H^1_0(\Omega)}.
\end{equation}
The Lax--Milgram theorem then yields existence and uniqueness of \(u\) and the estimate (\ref{eq:apriori}). This completes the proof of Theorem \ref{thm:existence}.

\section*{Galerkin approximation and energy estimates}
For a constructive outline, take a sequence of finite-dimensional subspaces \(V_m\subset H^1_0(\Omega)\) with \(\overline{\bigcup_m V_m}=H^1_0(\Omega)\). The Galerkin method seeks \(u_m\in V_m\) such that
\begin{equation}\label{eq:gal}
a(u_m,v)=L(v) \quad\forall v\in V_m.
\end{equation}
The same coercivity argument on \(V_m\) yields uniqueness of \(u_m\). Uniform energy estimates follow from (\ref{eq:apriori}), giving \(\{u_m\}\) bounded in \(H^1_0(\Omega)\). By weak compactness one extracts a subsequence converging weakly to \(u\) which, by density of the union of \(V_m\), satisfies the weak form (\ref{eq:weakform}).

\section*{Remarks}
This outline extends to coercive second-order elliptic operators with variable coefficients provided uniform ellipticity holds. The Poincar\'e constant and domain regularity affect the explicit constant in (\ref{eq:apriori}). The same strategy is commonly used as a template for numerical analysis and finite element convergence proofs via Céa's lemma and approximation estimates.

